Railway error

How directory looks

Why this is happening ? And how can i fix it ?

answer: "local time" means local time ZONE (or rather offset from UTC)

Querying mongodb documents based on overlapping conditions

I have a collection that is supposed to keep track of two values that increment throughout the day, split by days.

The way the documents are structured:

{
  year: number,
  month: number,
  day: number,
  valueA: number,
  valueB: number,
}

This works like a charm for inserting the values quickly, as I can just create a new date object, find the one with matching date values and increment those values (it' not always both, just as an example).

let date = new Date();
await collection.findOneAndUpdate(
    { day: date.getDate(), month: date.getMonth(), year: date.getFullYear() },
    { $inc: { valueA: 1, valueB: 1 }, $setOnInsert: { createdOn: date } },
    { upsert: true }
)

Thus I don't need to struggle with finding the "createdOn" date that happens to be on the same day.

However where I'm struggling is to get these values in a timeframe. My attempt was this:

this.pageStats.find({
    year: { $gte: start.getFullYear(), $lte: end.getFullYear() },
    month: { $gte: start.getMonth(), $lte: end.getMonth() },
    day: { $gte: start.getDate(), $lte: end.getDate() },
});

But this fails to deliver the expected results as if I for example want to get the data from 2023-01-01 until 2023-02-02, it will only give me 01-01, 01-02, 02-01 and 02-02.

I chose this layout as it makes it easy to get the date and insert the values grouped by the day, as that will happen hundreds to thousands of times per hour, while the request is something much less common so a less efficient query is acceptable. I'm also open to alternative data structures that make both inserting and requesting the data fast and efficient.

update config replication of mongodb sharded database access point mongos during run-time

I'm building a sharded MongoDB cluster, which I want to manage automatically. To achieve this I build the normal setup of a sharded db with:

  • 3 replications of the config db
  • 3 replications of shard "a" (initially only one but by growing the node size the number of shards increase)
  • 3 replications of the mongodb access points "mongos"

To connect the config db with the mongos instance I used the following command:

mongos --configdb "cfg/<ip_of_config_server_1>:<port_of_config_instance>,cfg/<ip_of_config_server_2>:<port_of_config_instance>,cfg/<ip_of_config_server_3>:<port_of_config_instance>" --fork --logpath <some_path> --port <some_port>

Now my problem is if one of the config servers is removed from the cluster (or goes down) and another is added, I need to update the mongos instance.

I just don't know how to do this without shutting down the mongos instance and rerunning this command, and thus causing downtime.

Does any of you know an approach or best practices for this situation?
answer: @Sbodd While SWT supports multiple displays on Windows, that is the only platform that supports multiple displays. If you are working on a project that is expected to build and run on Mac or Linux (such as Eclipse itself), it should be safe to assume there is only one display. Unless your application is doing so much painting of so many windows on so many monitors that it is impossible to push that many pixels from a single core, the use of multiple displays is a design flaw that limits portability (and/or permits bad practices like running long jobs on a UI thread), not an asset.

How do I merge array of objects with array of ObjectIds into one unique list in MongoDB?

I have a few documents that looks like this:

_id: ObjectId('232be4e2fd568670ec11d98b'),
name: 'Discord',
type: 'A',
devices: [
    ObjectId('642be505fd568670ec11d10c'),
    ObjectId('552be45cfd568670ec30d779')
],
endpoints: [
    {
        refId: ObjectId('641316fd596514e63a2121ca')
    },
    {
        refId: ObjectId('642bd725c7e5ec334ee17ce7')
    },
    {
        refId: ObjectId('552be45cfd568670ec30d779')
    }
]

_id: ObjectId('642c073643aaf70eee741e05'),
name: 'Twitter',
type: 'A',
devices: [
    ObjectId('642c072b37e4e956dfed39a0'),
    ObjectId('642c0730aa06dc1f7906b9a3')
]

_id: ObjectId('642c07b2fb3917c094e30734'),
name: 'Facebook',
type: 'A'

I'm trying to turn this into a document with _id and devices which is an array of unique ObjectIds. And be aware that endpoints and devices can be non-existing.

The result should look like this:

_id: ObjectId('232be4e2fd568670ec11d98b'),
devices: [
    ObjectId('642be505fd568670ec11d10c'),
    ObjectId('552be45cfd568670ec30d779'),
    ObjectId('641316fd596514e63a2121ca'),
    ObjectId('642bd725c7e5ec334ee17ce7')
]

_id: ObjectId('642c073643aaf70eee741e05'),
devices: [
    ObjectId('642c072b37e4e956dfed39a0'),
    ObjectId('642c0730aa06dc1f7906b9a3')
]

_id: ObjectId('642c07b2fb3917c094e30734'),
devices: [
]

I have to use group, but how do I concat the two arrays into one unique array? I've tried something like this:

{
    $group: {
        _id: '$_id',
        endpoints: {
            $addToSet: '$endpoints.refId'
        },
        devices: {
            $push: '$devices'
        }
    }
}

But already here I get issues if the arrays does not exist..
answer: @jmarkmurphy - I guess it depends on how close you want to get to Java's HashMap. An RPG array, even with data structures, isn't what I would consider very close. You don't have the O(1) lookup. You don't have enforcement of unique keys. The built-in arrays don't have dynamic sizing (though I know there are third-party libraries for that). And I'm not sure you can handle *arbitrary* types with a data structure array, other than to use pointers (adding implementation complexity or API complexity or both). To me, these are pretty important reasons for choosing HashMap in the first place.
